Review More settings
No the video is not for kids

Allow automatic chapters
Auto places and concepts
Add tags - use more than 400 characters
Allow embedding
Select proper Category
Comments ON
Monetize ON if applicable
Customize Ad breaks if video is longer than 8 minutes
This helps is happen in correct place in your video
Review Ad Suitability
End Screens
Add 1 video to reference users to watch next
Publish as Private first and ensure it looks good before making public. 
Once the video is published, write a comment on the video as a call to action for users and PIN it to the top of the list.

text: Another SUPER IMPORTANT tip a lot of creators overlook - adding timestamps for each section of your video (use some of those keywords you were talking about LOL). People watching are more likely to skip bits they find boring and go to the next most interesting "section" of your video if you include them, rather than leave the video entirely. They also help tremendously when you are looking at the video analytics as they help you at lot when looking at the audience retention graph. Cheers, Stephen Spry.

author: @Thebellsmum

text:
No, the filename itself does not impact video performance or SEO on YouTube. When you upload a video, YouTube doesn't consider the file name for ranking, recommendations, or search visibility. What does matter are the following elements:

    Title: A clear, engaging, and keyword-optimized title is crucial for search rankings and viewer interest.
    Description: Detailed descriptions with relevant keywords help YouTube's algorithm understand your content and improve discoverability.
    Tags: These further categorize your video and aid in being shown to relevant audiences.
    Thumbnail: Custom thumbnails grab attention and improve click-through rates.
    Closed Captions: Adding captions helps accessibility and can improve search rankings.
    Video Content: Content relevance, engagement, and watch time are key ranking factors.

While filenames don‚Äôt directly matter, a well-organized file naming system can help you manage and locate your own content better.

text:
¬†@LifeJourneyus¬† 

Oh yes, I film in the moment. For example, I might start recording when I drop off my son and keep the camera rolling as I head to my next stop to run errands. I don't pause the filming during this time, so it ends up being a 15-minute clip‚Äîpretty much what people consider a normal video length. But that's just one segment of my day. Then, I start a new clip when I enter the next location, filming until I get back to my car. I'll place the camera on the dash and keep recording until it becomes too awkward to hold the phone and film while doing what I need to do. Essentially, I film my entire day as if you're right there with me, walking alongside me.
